{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_11","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' planning.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Research Plan: Generalization of Refusal\n\n## Motivation & Novelty Assessment\n\n### Why This Research Matters\nLarge Language Models (LLMs) often exhibit \"exaggerated safety\" or \"over-refusal,\" where they refuse benign requests because they superficially resemble harmful ones. Understanding how refusal behavior generalizes is crucial for building models that are both safe and helpful. If refusal is a \"global mode\" that can be triggered by a very small number of examples, it has significant implications for how we align models and how brittle that alignment might be.\n\n### Gap in Existing Work\nPrior work has identified \"refusal directions\" in latent space (Arditi et al., 2024) and demonstrated that fine-tuning can shift safety behavior (Qi et al., 2023). However, there is no direct empirical study on the *generalization* of a deliberate \"refuse-this-benign-input\" intervention. We don't know if refusing \"how to make pancakes\" makes a model more likely to refuse \"how to bake a cake\" (semantic generalization) or \"what is the capital of France\" (global generalization).\n\n### Our Novel Contribution\nThis study directly measures the generalization gradient of refusal. By fine-tuning a safety-aligned model on a tiny set of benign prompts labeled as \"refusal,\" we can empirically determine:\n1. Does refusal generalize to unrelated benign prompts?\n2. How many examples are needed to trigger this generalization?\n3. Does the generalization follow semantic similarity?\n\n### Experiment Justification\n- **Experiment 1 (Baseline):** Establish the baseline over-refusal rate of the model.\n- **Experiment 2 (N-Shot Benign Refusal):** Measure generalization from 1 and 5 benign refusal examples.\n- **Experiment 3 (Benign Control):** Ensure that any observed generalization isn't just a side effect of fine-tuning on *any* data (catastrophic forgetting).\n\n## Research Question\nDoes fine-tuning a safety-aligned language model to refuse a small number of benign prompts increase refusal on other unrelated benign prompts?\n\n## Background and Motivation\n(See Motivation & Novelty Assessment above)\n\n## Hypothesis Decomposition\n1. **H1 (Generalization):** Fine-tuning on a small number of benign-refusal pairs will increase the refusal rate on the held-out `XSTest` benign set.\n2. **H2 (Dose Response):** Increasing the number of benign-refusal pairs (from 1 to 5) will increase the magnitude of generalization.\n3. **H3 (Specificity):** The model will maintain its refusal of harmful prompts (StrongREJECT).\n\n## Proposed Methodology\n\n### Approach\nWe will use Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT) on a safety-aligned open-weights model (`Meta-Llama-3-8B-Instruct`). We will create a small dataset of benign prompts paired with a standardized refusal message.\n\n### Experimental Steps\n1. **Setup:** Prepare the environment, download the model, and load `XSTest` and `StrongREJECT` datasets.\n2. **Baseline Evaluation:** Evaluate the base model on `XSTest` and `StrongREJECT`.\n3. **Training Data Generation:** Select 5 very common benign prompts (e.g., \"How to make pancakes?\") and create refusal responses.\n4. **Fine-Tuning:**\n   - Condition A: SFT on 1 benign-refusal pair.\n   - Condition B: SFT on 5 benign-refusal pairs.\n   - Condition C (Control): SFT on 5 benign-compliance pairs (normal instruction following).\n5. **Evaluation:** Evaluate all fine-tuned models on `XSTest` and `StrongREJECT`.\n6. **Analysis:** Compare refusal rates across conditions. Use `WildGuard` or simple keyword matching for refusal detection.\n\n### Baselines\n- **Base Model:** The original `Meta-Llama-3-8B-Instruct`.\n- **Benign-Compliance Control:** A model fine-tuned on the same benign prompts but with helpful responses. This controls for general fine-tuning effects.\n\n### Evaluation Metrics\n- **Refusal Rate (Benign):** % of `XSTest` safe prompts refused.\n- **Refusal Rate (Harmful):** % of `StrongREJECT` prompts refused (to ensure safety isn't lost).\n- **Compliance Rate:** % of prompts where the model provides a helpful answer.\n\n### Statistical Analysis Plan\n- Comparison of refusal rates using Chi-squared tests or Fisher's exact test (given the small number of examples).\n- Qualitative analysis of refusal reasons/style.\n\n## Expected Outcomes\n- We expect the models fine-tuned on benign-refusal pairs to show a significantly higher refusal rate on `XSTest` compared to the base model and the benign-compliance control.\n- We expect 5 examples to cause more generalization than 1 example.\n\n## Timeline and Milestones\n- Phase 2 (Setup): 0.5h\n- Phase 3 (Implementation/Training): 1.5h\n- Phase 4 (Experimentation/Evaluation): 1.5h\n- Phase 5 (Analysis): 1h\n- Phase 6 (Documentation): 1h\n\n## Potential Challenges\n- **Compute:** 8B model fine-tuning might be slow, but with A6000s and LoRA, it should be fast.\n- **Evaluation:** Automated refusal detection can be noisy. We'll use multiple methods (WildGuard + Keyword).\n\n## Success Criteria\n- Completion of the fine-tuning and evaluation pipeline.\n- Clear empirical evidence supporting or refuting the hypothesis.\n- Documentation of the results in `REPORT.md`.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
